    <!-- Add Activity -->

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <title>Comprehensive Activity: The Variation Explorer</title>

            <title>Part 1: Discovery (Inverse Variation)</title>
            <p><em>Objective:</em> To discover the relationship between length and width with a fixed area.</p>
            <p><em>Scenario:</em> You have 24 identical square tiles. You must arrange them into a single solid rectangle.</p>

            <title>Table 5.3.1</title>
                <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Rectangle</cell>
                        <cell>Width (<m>x</m>)</cell>
                        <cell>Length (<m>y</m>)</cell>
                        <cell>Product (<m>x \times y</m>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>A</cell>
                        <cell>1</cell>
                        <cell>24</cell>
                        <cell><m>1 \times 24 = 24</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>B</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell>12</cell>
                        <cell><m>2 \times 12 = 24</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>C</cell>
                        <cell>3</cell>
                        <cell><strong>8</strong></cell>
                        <cell><m>3 \times 8 = 24</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>D</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell><strong>6</strong></cell>
                        <cell><m>4 \times 6 = 24</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>E</cell>
                        <cell>6</cell>
                        <cell><strong>4</strong></cell>
                        <cell><m>6 \times 4 = 24</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>F</cell>
                        <cell>8</cell>
                        <cell><strong>3</strong></cell>
                        <cell><m>8 \times 3 = 24</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>

            <p><em>Key Concept:</em> This is <em>Inverse Variation</em>. As <m>x</m> increases, <m>y</m> decreases.</p>
            <p><em>Formula:</em> <m>y = \frac{k}{x}</m> or <m>xy = k</m> (where <m>k = 24</m>).</p>

            <title>Part 2: Expansion (Joint Variation)</title>
            <p><em>Objective:</em> To observe how three variables work together to determine a total.</p>
            <p><em>Scenario:</em> Imagine your 24 tiles are now 3D blocks. The <em>Volume (<m>V</m>)</em> of a box varies jointly with its <em>Length (<m>L</m>)</em>, <em>Width (<m>W</m>)</em>, and <em>Height (<m>H</m>)</em>.</p>
            <p><em>The Formula:</em> <m>V = kLWH</m> (For these blocks, <m>k = 1</m>)</p>
            <p><em>Task:</em> Complete the dimensions for a fixed Volume of <em>48 cubic units</em>.</p>

               <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Prism</cell>
                        <cell>Length (<m>L</m>)</cell>
                        <cell>Width (<m>W</m>)</cell>
                        <cell>Height (<m>H</m>)</cell>
                        <cell>Volume (<m>V</m>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>G</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell>3</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell>48</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>H</cell>
                        <cell>6</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell><strong>4</strong></cell>
                        <cell>48</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>I</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell><strong>12</strong></cell>
                        <cell>48</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>

            <p><em>Key Concept:</em> In <em>Joint Variation</em>, the result (<m>V</m>) depends on the product of multiple variables. If any one of them increases, the volume increases.</p>

            <title>Part 3: Complexity (Combined Variation)</title>
            <p><em>Objective:</em> To solve problems where one variable increases the result while another decreases it.</p>
            <p><em>Scenario: The Flooring Project</em></p>
            <p>A contractor's <em>Time (<m>T</m>)</em> to finish a job varies directly with the <em>Area (<m>A</m>)</em> of the room but inversely with the <em>Number of Workers (<m>w</m>)</em>.</p>
            <p><em>The Formula:</em> <m>T = \frac{k A}{w}</m></p>
            <p><em>Calculation Challenge:</em></p>
            <p>Suppose the constant <m>k = 0.5</m>. A crew is assigned to a <em>400 sq. ft.</em> lobby.</p>
            <ol>
                <li><em>With 2 workers:</em> <m>T = \frac{0.5 \times 400}{2} = \mathbf{100}</m> <em>hours.</em></li>
                <li><em>With 5 workers:</em> <m>T = \frac{0.5 \times 400}{5} = \mathbf{40}</m> <em>hours.</em></li>
            </ol>
            <p>Notice how the Area (<m>A</m>) "pulls" the time up (more work), but the Workers (<m>w</m>) "pull" the time down (more help).</p>

            <title>Part 4: Summary Table</title>
                <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Variation Type</cell>
                        <cell>General Formula</cell>
                        <cell>Real-World Example</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><strong>Inverse</strong></cell>
                        <cell><m>y = \frac{k}{x}</m></cell>
                        <cell>Speed vs. Time to travel a fixed distance.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><strong>Joint</strong></cell>
                        <cell><m>y = kxz</m></cell>
                        <cell>Area of a triangle (<m>A = \frac{1}{2}bh</m>).</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><strong>Combined</strong></cell>
                        <cell><m>y = \frac{kx}{z}</m></cell>
                        <cell>Fuel needed (<m>F</m>) varies with distance (<m>d</m>) and speed (<m>s</m>), but inversely with fuel efficiency (<m>e</m>).</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>

            <title>Final Task: The "Predictor"</title>
            <p>If a car's transport fare (<m>F</m>) varies jointly with fuel price (<m>P</m>) and distance (<m>d</m>), but inversely with the number of passengers (<m>n</m>):</p>
            <ul>
                <li>What happens to the price per person if the distance doubles? <em>(Increase/Decrease)</em></li>
                <li>What happens to the price per person if you add more friends to the car? <em>(Increase/Decrease)</em></li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
    </activity>

