    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>Since you've already mastered direct variation, the jump to <strong>Joint</strong> and <strong>Combined</strong> variation is simply about adding more "players" to the equation.</p>
    
        <p>
          <em>1. Joint Variation: The Power of "And"</em>  
        </p>
        <p>Joint variation occurs when a quantity depends on two or more other quantities. Think of it as <strong>Direct Variation multiplied.</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><em>Equation: </em><m>y = kxz</m></li>
            <li>The result (<m>y</m>) is directly proportional to the <strong>product</strong> of the other variables. If <m>x</m> stays the same but <m>z</m> doubles, <m>y</m> doubles. If <em>both</em> <m>x</m> and <m>z</m> double, <m>y</m> increases by four times (<m>2 \times 2</m>).</li>
            <li> All independent variables sit in the <strong>numerator</strong>. There is no division involved.</li>
            <li><em>Example:</em> The Area of a triangle (<m>A = \frac{1}{2}bh</m>). The area varies jointly with the base and the height.</li>
        </ul>

        <em>2. Combined Variation: The Tug-of-War</em>
        <p>Combined variation is the "all-in-one" model. It involves at least one <strong>direct/joint</strong> relationship and at least one <strong>inverse</strong> relationship happening at the same time.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><m>y = \frac{kx}{z}</m></li>
            <li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Variables in the <strong>numerator</strong> (<m>x</m>) pull the result <strong>up</strong>.</li>
                    <li>Variables in the <strong>denominator</strong> (<m>z</m>) pull the result <strong>down</strong>.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Look for problems that say "Varies directly with A ... <strong>and inversely</strong> with B."</li>
            <li><em>Example:</em> <p>The gas pressure (<m>P</m>) in a container varies directly with the temperature (<m>T</m>) but inversely with the volume (<m>V</m>).</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><em>Equation:</em> <m>P = \frac{kT}{V}</m></li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <em>Summary</em>
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Feature</cell>
                <cell>Joint Variation</cell>
                <cell>Combined Variation</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><strong>Equation Structure</strong></cell>
                <cell><m>y = kxz</m></cell>
                <cell><m>y = \frac{kx}{z}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><strong>Visualizing the Formula</strong></cell>
                <cell>A single line of multiplication.</cell>
                <cell>A fraction (numerator vs. denominator).</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><strong>How <m>k</m> is Found</strong></cell>
                <cell><m>k = \frac{y}{xz}</m></cell>
                <cell><m>k = \frac{yz}{x}</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The cost of painting a wall (<m>C</m>) varies jointly with its length (<m>l</m>) and its height (<m>h</m>). If a wall 10 meters long and 3 meters high costs Ksh300 to paint, how much will it cost to paint a wall 15 meters long and 4 meters high?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: Since it is joint variation, use <m>C = klh</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute the known values (<m>C=300, l=10, h=3</m>).</p>
            <p><m>300 = k(10)(3)</m></p>
            <p><m>300 = 30k \rightarrow k = 10</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>C = 10lh</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new wall: Substitute the new values (<m>l=15, h=4</m>).</p>
            <p><m>C = 10(15)(4)</m></p>
            <p><m>C = 10(60) = 600</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> The cost will be Ksh600.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The pressure (<m>P</m>) of a gas varies directly with its temperature (<m>T</m>) and inversely with its volume (<m>V</m>). A gas has a pressure of 150 units when the temperature is 300K and the volume is 20 liters. Find the pressure when the temperature is 400K and the volume is 10 liters.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: Combined variation uses <m>P = \frac{kT}{V}</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>P=150, T=300, V=20</m>.</p>
            <p><m>150 = \frac{k(300)}{20}</m></p>
            <p><m>150 = 15k \rightarrow k = 10</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>P = \frac{10T}{V}</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new pressure: Substitute <m>T=400, V=10</m>.</p>
            <p><m>P = \frac{10(400)}{10}</m></p>
            <p><m>P = 400</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> The new pressure is 400 units.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The weight (<m>W</m>) that a flatbed truck can carry varies jointly with the number of axles (<m>a</m>) and the tire pressure (<m>p</m>). A truck with 2 axles and 80 psi tire pressure can carry 16 tons. How many tons can a truck with 3 axles and 90 psi carry?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: <m>W = kap</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>W=16, a=2, p=80</m>.</p>
            <p><m>16 = k(2)(80)</m></p>
            <p><m>16 = 160k \rightarrow k = 0.1</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>W = 0.1ap</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new weight: Substitute <m>a=3, p=90</m>.</p>
            <p><m>W = 0.1(3)(90)</m></p>
            <p><m>W = 0.1(270) = 27</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> The truck can carry 27 tons.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The frequency (<m>f</m>) of a vibrating string varies directly as the square root of the tension (<m>t</m>) and inversely as the length (<m>l</m>) of the string. If a string 2 meters long with a tension of 100N has a frequency of 40Hz, what is the frequency if the length is 1 meter and the tension is 400N?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: <m>f = \frac{k\sqrt{t}}{l}</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>f=40, l=2, t=100</m>.</p>
            <p><m>40 = \frac{k\sqrt{100}}{2}</m></p>
            <p><m>40 = \frac{10k}{2} \rightarrow 40 = 5k \rightarrow k = 8</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>f = \frac{8\sqrt{t}}{l}</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new frequency: Substitute <m>l=1, t=400</m>.</p>
            <p><m>f = \frac{8\sqrt{400}}{1}</m></p>
            <p><m>f = 8(20) = 160</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> The new frequency is 160 Hz.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>The simple interest (<m>I</m>) earned on a savings account varies jointly with the principal amount (<m>P</m>) and the time in years (<m>t</m>). If Ksh500 earns Ksh60 in 3 years, how much interest will Ksh800 earn in 5 years?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: <m>I = kPt</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>I=60, P=500, t=3</m>.</p>
            <p><m>60 = k(500)(3)</m></p>
            <p><m>60 = 1500k \rightarrow k = \frac{60}{1500} = 0.04</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>I = 0.04Pt</m>. (Note: <m>k</m> here represents the annual interest rate of 4%).</p>
            <p>Solve for the new interest: Substitute <m>P=800, t=5</m>.</p>
            <p><m>I = 0.04(800)(5)</m></p>
            <p><m>I = 32(5) = 160</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> The interest earned will be Ksh160.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- Add exercises -->

    <exercises>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>The amount of cement (C) required to plaster a floor varies jointly with the area of the floor (A) and the thickness of the plaster (t). If 10 m² of floor requires 20 kg of cement when the thickness is 2 cm, how much cement is required for 15 m² with a thickness of 3 cm?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: <m>C = kAt</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>C=20, A=10, t=2</m>.</p>
            <p><m>20 = k(10)(2)</m></p>
            <p><m>20 = 20k \rightarrow k = 1</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>C = At</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new amount: Substitute <m>A=15, t=3</m>.</p>
            <p><m>C = (15)(3) = 45</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> 45 kg of cement is required.</p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>The number of chickens (N) on a poultry farm varies jointly with the area of the farm (A) and the number of workers (W). If a farm of 100 m² with 5 workers can support 200 chickens, how many chickens can a farm of 150 m² with 8 workers support?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: <m>N = kAW</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>N=200, A=100, W=5</m>.</p>
            <p><m>200 = k(100)(5)</m></p>
            <p><m>200 = 500k \rightarrow k = 0.4</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>N = 0.4AW</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new number: Substitute <m>A=150, W=8</m>.</p>
            <p><m>N = 0.4(150)(8)</m></p>
            <p><m>N = 0.4(1200) = 480</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> The farm can support 480 chickens.</p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>The cost of painting a wall (C) varies jointly with the area of the wall (A) and the number of coats (n). If painting 20 m² with 2 coats costs Ksh 400, what is the cost of painting 30 m² with 3 coats?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: <m>C = kAn</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>C=400, A=20, n=2</m>.</p>
            <p><m>400 = k(20)(2)</m></p>
            <p><m>400 = 40k \rightarrow k = 10</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>C = 10An</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new cost: Substitute <m>A=30, n=3</m>.</p>
            <p><m>C = 10(30)(3)</m></p>
            <p><m>C = 10(90) = 900</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> The cost will be Ksh 900.</p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>The volume of water (V) flowing through a pipe varies directly as the pressure (P) and inversely as the length of the pipe (L). If 10 liters flow through a 5 m pipe under 2 atm pressure, how much water flows through a 10 m pipe under 3 atm pressure?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: <m>V = \frac{kP}{L}</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>V=10, P=2, L=5</m>.</p>
            <p><m>10 = \frac{k(2)}{5}</m></p>
            <p><m>10 = \frac{2k}{5} \rightarrow 50 = 2k \rightarrow k = 25</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>V = \frac{25P}{L}</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new volume: Substitute <m>P=3, L=10</m>.</p>
            <p><m>V = \frac{25(3)}{10}</m></p>
            <p><m>V = \frac{75}{10} = 7.5</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> 7.5 liters of water will flow.</p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>The brightness of a light (B) varies directly as the square of the voltage (V) and inversely as the distance from the source (d). If the brightness is 100 units at 10V and 2m distance, what is the brightness at 15V and 3m distance?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Write the general formula: <m>B = \frac{kV^2}{d}</m>.</p>
            <p>Find the constant (<m>k</m>): Substitute <m>B=100, V=10, d=2</m>.</p>
            <p><m>100 = \frac{k(10)^2}{2}</m></p>
            <p><m>100 = \frac{100k}{2} \rightarrow 100 = 50k \rightarrow k = 2</m></p>
            <p>Write the specific equation: <m>B = \frac{2V^2}{d}</m>.</p>
            <p>Solve for the new brightness: Substitute <m>V=15, d=3</m>.</p>
            <p><m>B = \frac{2(15)^2}{3}</m></p>
            <p><m>B = \frac{2(225)}{3}</m></p>
            <p><m>B = \frac{450}{3} = 150</m></p>
            <p><strong>Answer:</strong> The brightness will be 150 units.</p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    </exercises>

